description:
The adapter/connector registry is process-global and keyed only by a guessable adapter id. `registerAdapter`/`getAdapter` use a single `Map<string,SourceAdapter>` (src/packs/registry.ts:6-18) populated from ALL sidecars in one shared dir (loadPacks → listSidecars, src/packs/loadPacks.ts:73-99), and the cred files are read by id from one shared workspace. The pull route gates only the CALLER's own workflow, then dereferences an attacker-supplied global id:

```js
app.post("/api/adapters/:id/pull", async (req, reply) => {
  await guardData("connector.edit"); // checks caller's OWN active workflow only
  return await ingestPull((req.params as any).id, { limit });
});
```
`ingestPull` does `const adapter = getAdapter(adapterId)` (src/packs/ingest.ts:50) — another tenant's connector — runs its code with that connector's stored credentials (read by id in src/packs/connector/runtime.ts:228 / writeFileSync ctx), and `store.insert(...)` stamps the rows into the CALLER's workflow namespace (src/twin/projection-store.ts:262-276). The attacker then reads them via `GET /api/bc/:bc/raw`. `POST /api/bc/:bc/adapter/:id/test` (src/http/bc-routes.ts:152) and the chat tool `adapter_dry_run` (src/chat/tools.ts:598, no guardData) return the pulled rows directly in the response. `GET /api/adapters` (src/http/routes.ts:272, no guardData) enumerates every tenant's adapter ids so no guessing is needed.

copyConnectorCredentials(fromId, toId) authorizes nothing about the source: it only checks that both ids resolve in the PROCESS-GLOBAL sidecar/credential store, then blindly copies the source's plaintext secret blob into the destination. Quoted evidence (orchestrate.ts:147-158):
  export async function copyConnectorCredentials(fromId, toId) {
    if (fromId === toId) throw ...;
    if (!readSidecar(toId)) throw ...;
    if (!readSidecar(fromId)) throw ...;   // <-- existence only, NO org/workflow check
    const creds = readCredentials(fromId); // <-- reads ANOTHER tenant's secret
    ...
    writeCredentials(toId, creds);         // <-- lands it in the attacker's connector
  }
The only authorization is the chat layer's guardData('connector.edit') (tools.ts TOOL_WRITE_ACTIONS line 40), and that gate resolves its resource from currentWorkflowId() — the ATTACKER's active workflow (authz.ts:52-59). PDP step-0 therefore compares org A vs org A and ALLOWS. The source connector id (org B's) is attacker-controlled free text never run through the PDP. handleCopyConnectorCredentials (tools.ts:761) additionally has NO confirmed:true gate, so a single prompt-injected turn can invoke it with no human in the loop. Credentials themselves are stored plaintext, keyed only by id, in one global dir (runtime.ts:42, writeCredentials/readCredentials runtime.ts:223-232) and registered cross-org by loadPacks (loadPacks.ts:73-99). Once the blob is in the attacker's connector they can (a) reach org B's backend systems directly and (b) recover the literal secret VALUES by calling build_connector with instructions that echo ctx.credentials into returned rows, then ingest_connector and read them from the explorer — full value disclosure, not just field names.

The connector-builder chat endpoints persist the full builder conversation in a PROCESS-GLOBAL directory keyed by an attacker-reconstructable slug, with no tenant scoping and no PDP gate. GET handler:

```
app.get("/api/bc/:bc/connector-chat", async (req, reply) => {
  const bc = resolveBc((req.params as any).bc);
  if (!bc) return reply.code(404)...;
  const target = String((req.query as any)?.target ?? "");
  ...
  const id = connectorChatId(bc, target);
  const chat = readChat(id);
  return { id, messages: chat?.messages ?? [], updatedAt: chat?.updatedAt ?? null };
});
```

`connectorChatId(bc, target)` is `slug(`${bc}-${target}`)` (journal.ts:47-53) and `readChat` reads `.qlerify/connector-journal/<id>.chat.json` (journal.ts:20,56,66) — a single shared, NON-org/NON-workflow-scoped directory (the file header even states 'Storage is process-global ... security deferred'). `resolveBc` only canonicalizes against the CALLER's own loaded model, and `target` is a free-form query param, so the chat id is fully attacker-controlled: an attacker points their own workflow at a model whose bounded-context name slugs to any prefix and sets `target` to the remainder to reproduce ANY victim chat id. The repo's own .gitignore documents that this log 'may contain pasted secrets in the chat log', so the disclosed data routinely includes source-system credentials a victim pasted into the builder. The sibling /api/connectors routes call `guardData(...)`; these chat routes call NONE — and even an org-scoped PDP check would not help because the key space itself is global. The matching PUT (line 287) and DELETE (line 299) let an attacker overwrite or wipe another tenant's chat, and injected chat content is later fed back to the connector-codegen LLM (prompt-injection surface).

While per-org Anthropic/Qlerify BYOK keys are AES-256-GCM encrypted at rest, the credentials an org configures for AI-built connectors (which authenticate to real downstream source systems — API keys, bearer tokens, DB/AWS/basic-auth secrets) are written to disk in cleartext:

```
/** Store the plaintext credentials blob (any shape). PoC — security deferred. */
export function writeCredentials(id: string, creds: Record<string, unknown>): void {
  ensureWorkspace();
  writeFileSync(credPath(id), JSON.stringify(creds ?? {}, null, 2) + "\n");
}
```

`credPath` is `.qlerify/connectors/<id>.cred.json` (runtime.ts:110) on the same persisted volume that holds the DB and is shared across all tenants. The id space is the same global, attacker-reconstructable slug as the journal, and `copyConnectorCredentials(fromId, toId)` (orchestrate.ts:147-158) reads from ANY connector id and writes to ANY connector id with no org/workflow check — so a tenant can copy another tenant's stored source-system secrets into a connector they control and exfiltrate them by running that connector against an attacker-chosen endpoint. For an on-prem highest-bar deployment, leaving one class of secrets in world-readable cleartext while encrypting another is an inconsistent and exploitable secrets-at-rest gap.

Every EventLog read in the codebase is scoped with `eventLogOrgWhere()` (which folds in `workflowId` + `organizationId` from the resolved tenant context) — except the chat assistant's `get_event_log` tool, which queries the shared EventLog table by a user-supplied caseId with NO tenant filter:

```js
async function handleGetEventLog(caseId: string, limit: number) {
  const log = await prisma.eventLog.findMany({
    where: { caseId },                // <-- no eventLogOrgWhere()
    orderBy: { occurredAt: "desc" },
    take: limit,
    select: { eventName: true, eventRef: true, boundedContext: true, role: true, businessAt: true, occurredAt: true },
  });
  return { caseId, events: log };
}
```

The sibling HTTP route does it correctly: `prisma.eventLog.findMany({ where: caseId ? { caseId, ...eventLogOrgWhere() } : eventLogOrgWhere() })` (src/http/routes.ts:159-160), and `genericInstanceDetail` (used by the adjacent `get_case_details` tool) also scopes (src/twin/sim.ts:371). So this is a single missed call site introduced by the multi-tenant retrofit, not an intentional design. The `caseId` comes straight from the LLM tool argument (`String(args.caseId ?? "")`, tools.ts:393), which is driven by the end user's chat message. EventLog is a single shared Prisma table holding every org's domain-event history, so the unscoped query returns rows belonging to ANY organization/workflow.

The chat read tool queries the append-only EventLog by caseId with no tenant scope:

```js
const log = await prisma.eventLog.findMany({
  where: { caseId },
  orderBy: { occurredAt: "desc" },
  ...
});
```
Every other EventLog read folds in `eventLogOrgWhere()` (e.g. the HTTP equivalent `GET /sim/event-log`, src/http/routes.ts:159-160, and all of twin/sim.ts), which scopes to the active workflow + org. This handler is the lone exception, so a caller whose chat turn supplies a caseId belonging to another org/workflow receives that case's event rows. caseIds are random ids (newId), so this is not trivially enumerable, but it is a missing tenant predicate on a data-plane read and the rows can carry business-payload-derived fields.
